@startuml
title SongSpiration / MusicPin — Relacje tabel w bazie danych (ERD)

hide methods
skinparam classAttributeIconSize 0
skinparam linetype ortho

' Używamy "class" jako reprezentacji tabel (czytelne PK/FK w atrybutach)

class User <<table>> {
  {PK} id: uniqueidentifier
  email: nvarchar
  password_hash: nvarchar
  display_name: nvarchar
  avatar_url: nvarchar
  bio: nvarchar
  roles: nvarchar
  created_at: datetime2
  last_login: datet ime2
  is_email_verified: bit
}

class AuthToken <<table>> {
  {PK} id: uniqueidentifier
  {FK} user_id: uniqueidentifier
  token_hash: varbinary/nvarchar
  type: nvarchar  ' access|refresh
  expires_at: datetime2
  revoked_at: datetime2
  created_at: datetime2
}

class Pin <<table>> {
  {PK} id: uniqueidentifier
  {FK} owner_id: uniqueidentifier
  title: nvarchar
  description: nvarchar
  instrument: nvarchar
  visibility: nvarchar

  gp_file_location_or_blob: nvarchar/varbinary
  filename: nvarchar
  mime_type: nvarchar
  size: bigint
  checksum: nvarchar

  created_at: datetime2
  updated_at: datetime2
}

class Genre <<table>> {
  {PK} id: uniqueidentifier
  name: nvarchar
  slug: nvarchar
  {unique} slug
}

class PinGenre <<table>> {
  {PK}{FK} pin_id: uniqueidentifier
  {PK}{FK} genre_id: uniqueidentifier
}

class Like <<table>> {
  {PK}{FK} user_id: uniqueidentifier
  {PK}{FK} pin_id: uniqueidentifier
  created_at: datetime2
  ..constraints..
  {unique} (user_id, pin_id)
}

' ===== Relacje FK (kardynalności) =====
User "1" ||--o{ Pin : owner_id
User "1" ||--o{ AuthToken : user_id

User "1" ||--o{ Like : user_id
Pin  "1" ||--o{ Like : pin_id

Pin   "1" ||--o{ PinGenre : pin_id
Genre "1" ||--o{ PinGenre : genre_id

note right of Like
Unikatowa para (user_id, pin_id)
zapewnia, że użytkownik może
polubić dany pin max 1 raz.
end note

note right of PinGenre
Tabela łącznikowa realizująca
relację wiele-do-wielu Pin ↔ Genre.
PK złożony: (pin_id, genre_id).
end note

@enduml
